{{for|the administrative division of Korea under Japanese rule|Kōkai Prefecture}}
A {{nihongo|'''''kōkai'''''|公開}}, short for {{nihongo|'''''kōkai tokkyo kōhō'''''|公開特許公報}}, is a published, unexamined [[Japan]]ese [[patent application]], in contrast to the ''[[kokoku (patent law)|kokoku]]'' or ''tokkyo kōhō'', the examined and approved Japanese patent application.<ref>{{cite web | first1 = Mindy L. | last1 = Kotler | first2 = Gary W. | last2 = Hamilton | title = A guide to Japan's patent system | citeseerx = 10.1.1.124.6834 |date=November 1995 | page = 19 }}</ref> ''Kōkai'' means "open to the public", or "laid-open". ''Kōkai'' are published eighteen months after the earliest [[Paris Convention for the Protection of Industrial Property|priority]] date.

{{nihongo|'''''Tokukai'''''|特開}} is another shorthand for ''kōkai tokkyo kōhō'', taken from the first character of ''tokkyo'' (patent) and the second of ''kōkai''.

== See also ==
* [[Japanese patent law]]

