{{Infobox person | name = Meryle J. Reagon | image = <!-- filename only, no "File:" or "Image:" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software --> | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1942}} | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) --> | death_place = | nationality = American | other_names = | alma_mater = [[Tennessee State University]] | occupation = [[Civil rights movement]] activist | years_active = | known_for = [[Freedom Ride]]r | notable_works = | spouse = [[Frederick Leonard (activist)|Frederick Leonard]] | family = [[Cordell Reagon]], sister }} '''Meryle Joy Reagon''' is an American [[civil rights movement]] activist born in 1942. In June 1961, she participated in a [[Freedom Ride]] from [[Montgomery, Alabama]] to [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref name=CRDL>{{cite web|title=Reagon, Meryle Joy|url=http://crdl.usg.edu/people/r/reagon_meryle_joy/|website=Civil Rights Digital Library|accessdate=5 March 2018}}</ref> She is also known as the husband of another Freedom Rider, [[Frederick Leonard (activist)|Frederick Leonard]] and sister of [[Cordell Reagon]].
== Involvement in Freedom Ride on June 2, 1961 == Reagon was a 19 year old [[Tennessee State University]] student when she participated in a [[Freedom Ride]] from [[Montgomery, Alabama]] to [[Jackson, Mississippi]].<ref name=CRDL />
The [[Freedom Ride]] began at 7:30am which was two and a half hours before Judge Johnson's ruling.<ref name=RAYMOND>{{cite book|last1=Arsenault|first1=Raymond|title=Freedom Riders: 1961 and the Struggle for Racial Justice, PDF eBook Freedom Riders: 1961 and the Struggle for Racial Justice|date=2 November 2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199792429|page=211}}</ref> The group of [[Freedom Riders]] was led by [[SNCC]] veteran, [[Ruby Doris Smith-Robinson|Ruby Doris Smith]]. The group of riders included two students from Long Island, Reagon and [[Charles Butler (freedom rider)|Charles Butler]], along with three white male volunteers. <ref name=RAYMOND/> Later that afternoon, Reagon along with the others including Smith were arrested in [[Jackson, Mississippi]] at the [[Trailways]] terminal<ref name=CRDL/>, and taken to Hinds County Jail.<ref name=RAYMOND/> Four hours later, her brother, [[Cordell Reagon]] would later arrive at Hinds County Jail.<ref name=RAYMOND/>
