{{Infobox military installation | name = Xlejli Tower | native_name = It-Torri tax-Xlejli | location = [[Gudja]], [[Malta]] | image = Torri Xulliela 02.jpg | image_size = 300px | caption = View of the Xlejli Tower | type = [[Watchtower]] | coordinates = {{coord|35|50|59.9|N|14|30|27.6|E|type:landmark|display=inline}} | ownership = Private | controlledby = | open_to_public = No | built = Unknown | builder = Unknown | materials = Stone and glass<ref>Zammit Tabona, Kenneth (2015). [https://web.archive.org/web/20160504025250/http://www.mirandabooks.com/product/the-age-of-elegance/ "The Age of Elegance"]. Miranda Publishers. Archived on 4 March 2016.</ref> | height = | condition = Preserved }}
'''Xlejli Tower''' (formerly spelt '''Shilejli Tower''', {{lang-mt|Torri tax-Xlejli}} or ''Torri Xulliela''),<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cassar Pullicino|first1=Joseph|title=The Order of St. John in Maltese folk-memory|journal=Scientia|date=October–December 1949|volume=15|issue=4|page=156|url=http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Scientia%20(Malta)/Scientia.%2015(1949)4(Oct.-Dec.)/01.pdf|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417173522/http://melitensiawth.com/incoming/Index/Scientia%20(Malta)/Scientia.%2015(1949)4(Oct.-Dec.)/01.pdf|archivedate=17 April 2016}}</ref> also known as '''Bettina Tower''', is a [[tower]] in [[Gudja]], Malta. It was probably built as a [[watchtower]] since it has views over a large area of land. The age of the tower is not known, and it could date back to the Roman or medieval periods, or possibly a later reconstruction. The tower is now located in the grounds of [[Palazzo Dorell]], and it is closed to the public.
==History== Its date of construction is not known, but it might have Roman origins. According to {{Interlanguage link multi|Louis de Boisgelin|fr|3=Pierre-Marie-Louis de Boisgelin de Kerdu}}, the historian of the [[Knights Hospitaller|Order of St. John]], an urn full of Roman [[copper]] medals was found at the tower. The tower also has a round shape, similar to other [[Punic-Roman towers in Malta]].<ref name=lecrac/><ref name=mahoney>{{cite book|last=Mahoney|first=Leonardo|date=1994|editor=Henry Frendo and Oliver Friggieri|title=Malta Culture and Identity|chapter=Architecture|url=https://www.bdlbooks.com/culture/3326-malta-culture-and-identity.html|publisher=Books Distributors Limited|page=131|isbn=}}</ref> It is believed that the remains of an old and round building are those of a [[watchtower]]. The Xlejli Tower was built in the parametres of these remains in an architectural style to appear as a ‘ruined’ tower.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mahoney|first=Leonard|date=1996|title=5000 Years of Architecture in Malta||url=https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=zf0pAQAACAAJ&dq=5,000+years+of+architecture+in+Malta+Castellania&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj5m5KVlqfSAhWEfhoKHd46BzkQ6AEIGTAA|publisher=Valletta Pub.|isbn=9789990958157|page=100}}</ref>
The oldest reference to the tower dates back to 1570, when it was described as a lookout tower built in the 12th or 13th century. The tower was almost definitely built as a [[watchtower]], since it has views of the southern part of Malta, stretching from [[Bengħisa]] to the [[Grand Harbour]].<ref name=lecrac>{{cite web|last1=Graham|first1=Jimmy|title=Xlejli Tower, Bettina Palace|url=http://lecrac.blogspot.com.mt/2014/10/xlejli-tower-bettina-palace.html|website=Le Crac: Buildings of the Order of St.John of Jerusalem, of Rhodes and of Malta, at the Convent and in the provinces|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226013407/http://lecrac.blogspot.com.mt/2014/10/xlejli-tower-bettina-palace.html|archivedate=26 December 2015|date=7 October 2014}}</ref>
In the 17th century, the [[Palazzo Dorell]] was built close to the tower, and the latter was included in its grounds within a large walled garden. Since then, the tower has been closed for the public. The palace was the property of Marquees Bettina Testaferrata Dorell, and she restored the tower and decorated its interior. Due to this, it also became known as ''Bettina Tower'' after her.<ref name=lecrac/> She had actually named it<ref>Johnston, Shirley Jackewicz (2001), [https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=t-kVAQAAMAAJ&q=xlejli+tower&dq=xlejli+tower&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTm7Cz5frJAhUFXRoKHR0fDkwQ6AEIJTAC "Malte"], Random House Incorporated, {{ISBN|9780847822867}}, p. 176.</ref> as ''Xlejli'', which has a literal meaning of "tacked together" in old [[Maltese language|Maltese]].<ref>Chambry, D.; Trumb, David H. (1978), [https://books.google.com.mt/books?id=Zy0QAQAAMAAJ&q=xlejli+tower&dq=xlejli+tower&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTm7Cz5frJAhUFXRoKHR0fDkwQ6AEIGzAA "Country Life, Volume 165"], 1979, Nagel Publishers, {{ISBN|9782826307112}}, p. 844.</ref>
Some sources suggest that though the foundations of the old tower were retained on site, the present tower was built within the remains around 1780.<ref name=mahoney/> In [[World War II]], a bomb fell close to the tower, destroying a statue.<ref name=lecrac/> The bomb also destroyed an entire orchard.<ref name=mahoney/> The tower is built of Maltese limestone and purposely used shiny pieces of glass, with an appearance of a ruined tower( hence the name).<ref name=mahoney/>
